Communism is making a comeback in Russia.
Moscow—Over a year ago, I returned to my hometown of Moscow during a sabbatical from my teaching position at a US university.
My destination is not a bastion of free speech.
But in this place, some freedom still persists.
The opposition leader Alexei Navalny had traveled nationwide in an attempt to win support for politicians not under the control of the Kremlin.
Protest activities by the public have erupted.
Independent non-government organizations operate domestically.
Journalists and analysts are not necessarily aligned with the Kremlin's agenda.
And the Communist Party is widely regarded as a legacy from history.
Since then, Navalny has been imprisoned, and the protest movement he initiated has been suppressed.
Its anti-corruption foundation was dissolved for being "extremist," and its members are either in exile or under investigation.
Almost every day, journalists, media organizations, human rights advocates, or independent bodies are added to the "foreign agent" list — even worse, they are listed as "unwelcome persons."
Over the past year, Russia has found itself in a non-free condition, which, while not far off, has been particularly intense.
For example, in 2012, legislation was enacted to appoint foreign representatives, with the aim of undermining or disparaging organizations or individuals engaged in “political activities” and simultaneously receiving funding from abroad.
But the application of this law has become increasingly arbitrary, to the point that sharing a tweet is now grounds for being labeled as a foreign agent.
(The "unpopular" label could lead to your complete ban.
) This year alone, 101 additional entities were added to the list of foreign agents, setting a record.
A total of 359, including 88 media-related organizations and individuals, is cumulative.
According to the Russian government, the aforementioned "agents" must be included on the list because they "influence national politics."
But the core goal of news and propaganda work, of course, is to influence politics.
And that is precisely the problem: while President Vladimir Putin has positioned himself to continue controlling Russian politics in the foreseeable future, he perceives criticism as a survival threat.
Despite all this silence and persecution, it was an unlikely group, the Communist Party, that survived and became the only genuine opposition at the Kremlin.
This was largely due to Navalny’s “smart voting” strategy – encouraging people to support candidates most likely to defeat the Kremlin-backed contenders – and the Communists’ strong showing in last month’s parliamentary and regional elections.
According to official data, the Communist Party candidate won 18.9% of the votes for the State Duma (parliament), while the United Russia party, backed by the Kremlin, secured nearly 49.8%.
But the communists refused to acknowledge this outcome, insisting that the voting results were manipulated.
In fact, some experts estimated that they should have garnered about 30% of the votes, while United Russia should have received about 35%.
To many Russians, the Communists now seem more respected than Putin.
But they are no longer the original Communists.
Not only do they not deny earthly pleasures; on the contrary, the party members are fond of wearing fur coats, traveling abroad, driving foreign cars, and using social media.
Some people are millionaires – such as the charming agricultural chief Pavel Grudinin (who was forbidden from participating in last month’s election).
Despite the party still being led by Genady Zyuganov at the age of 77, it is increasingly influenced and supported by younger members.
Take Nikolai Bondarchuk, for example.
Bondaenko, nicknamed "Red Navalny," a 36-year-old, made serious criticisms of the poorly designed pension reform of 2018.
Not long ago, when a regional minister suggested that Russians should be able to eat better on a mere monthly salary of 3,500 rubles (about $50), Bondarenko recorded his efforts on his YouTube channel to prove the man wrong.
Despite being threatened with a ban on running for office, Bondarenko was still allowed to participate in last month's State Duma election.
Despite receiving support from Navalny's Smart Voting system, he still lost to the candidate of United Russia.
But his potential should not be overlooked: he recently wrote a headline for a protest against what he accused of “the state and government taking over United Russia.”
Then there is Anastasia Yudasova, who is 43 years old.
Like Bondarenko, she inexplicably lost the last election.
But she remains very — and increasingly — popular.
Thanks to the smart voting system, Ekaterina Engalicheva, another rising star and graceful newcomer, was elected to the Moscow City Duma in 2019.
Ironically, the Communist Party’s modernization reflects a yearning for the past: in 1917, Lenin’s Bolsheviks promised justice and equality; the nation they sought to realize, though strict, was not without fairness and kindness.
Similarly, like the liberal Navalny, today’s Communist Party represents a predictable and consistent vision under which someone’s fanciful ideas do not affect everyone.
It is precisely based on such logic that all of the Kremlin's opponents are increasingly joining forces: forming a unified opposition to United Russia, called simply "United Russia."
This situation is not limited to Russia.
In the recent parliamentary elections in the Czech Republic, Andrej Babiš – also known as the Czech Donald Trump – failed to continue as prime minister, as opposition alliances put aside their ideological differences with him and formed a common coalition, with its leader Petr Fiala likely set to lead the new government alongside another opposition alliance.
As Fiala put it, "people are tired of populists," and they want "normal, competent, and dignified politics."
The opposition in Hungary will also draw up a unified election list and field a single candidate for prime minister in next year's parliamentary elections.
Of course, the Czech Republic still operates under a democratic system, so Babiš is preparing to join the opposition forces.
Overthrowing Putin would be much more difficult, and it is not hard to anticipate that there will be further comprehensive measures aimed at crushing the Communist Party.
But such approaches also pose risks to the Kremlin.
The situation now is that the president claims that Russian democracy has not died and points to the presence of an "active opposition" as evidence, which suggests that he at least remains interested in pretending that Russia is not being steered toward near-totalitarianism.
Putin said he only wants stability.
But its regime is pushing Russia into more turbulent circumstances.
If the Kremlin were to be as fickle in devising and enforcing rules as it has been toward Russia’s liberals, driving the Communists underground, then social explosions become more likely.
And if it decides to no longer suppress it, the Russian Communists—yes, actual Communists—could become an不可忽视的力量. Here, I've translated "不容忽视的势力" as "unignorable force," which more accurately conveys the intended meaning in English.
